<subSubSection id="CE3B5FF54F955292D78DA0EE6419600D" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8E7B707AA14991C66B706162353AF9AB" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9E00DBCDDB32E694ABB51EE75FDE1996" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">The species epithet, sinuatum, is of Latin derivation and means winding or bent, referring to the shape of the extended epandrium in lateral view.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="16149A96F1C30132C4ACF417BD4C60CE" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="FF39C9AB172C603D7B1CF29662F5FC4A" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5EB88A21F712367E24868D687A8D2FA5" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
Although structures of the male terminalia of this species are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="F6D7351F9C468DC0749E7D948E932B66" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Hydrochasma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrochasma digitatum" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitatum">Hydrochasma digitatum</taxonomicName>
, they consistently differ in detail. This is particularly evident in the shape of the ventral, epandrial processes where in lateral view there is a basal, posterior notch, and the processes themselves are sinuous and not shallowly arched, as in 
<taxonomicName id="CECB8099656213C6D4F35E2350543BD4" class="Insecta" family="Ephydridae" genus="Hydrochasma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hydrochasma digitatum" order="Diptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="digitatum">Hydrochasma digitatum</taxonomicName>
. The sinuous profile of the ventral, epandrial process is the basis for the name of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
